# PentagonQBasis — the 9295-element size-8 ∅-flag basis (Phase 3.1)

**Phase 3.1 of the pentagon-Q axiom elimination.**

Provides the size-8 empty-typed flag basis enumerated by the Rust
`flag-algebra` crate and used by the SDP cert in `PentagonQCertificate`.

## Encoding

Each basis element is a 2-coloured triangle-free connected graph on 8
vertices, encoded as a 36-bit packed integer:

  * bits 0..27  = upper-triangular adjacency (28 bits)
                  bit position for edge (u, v) with u < v is `v*(v-1)/2 + u`.
  * bits 28..35 = vertex colours (8 bits)
                  bit `28+v` is the colour (0 or 1) of vertex `v`.

The colour bit follows the **Rust convention** (0=black, 1=red); the
Lean `CG2` colouring uses the swapped convention (1=black, 0=red, per
`feedback_colour_convention.md`). We propagate the colour bit directly
into the `CGraph 8` colour field — the propagation matches the Rust
output, so every consumer that reasons about cert coefficients can use
the Rust-side colour bit literally.

## Architecture

To avoid emitting 9295 individual flag `def`s (the BRRB `SdpFlags.lean`
shape, ~20 LOC/flag = ~180k LOC unscalable), we ship the basis as a
single comma-separated hex String literal `basisHexStr` of size
~93 KB, plus a runtime parser `parseHexNats` producing an
`Array Nat` of 9295 entries.

The `flagBasis (k : Fin 9295)` function decodes each entry to a
`CGraph 8` and lifts via `CGraph.toGenFlag` to a `GenFlag CG2
(GenFlagType.empty CG2)`. This is `noncomputable` (no real need to run
it; we only refer to it abstractly), but the underlying `CGraph 8` is
fully computable and amenable to `native_decide`.

